com.pump.text

Class TextDiff

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.pump.text.TextDiff

  • public class TextDiff
extends java.lang.Object
    This object can diff two Strings together to find the minimal amount of changes between the two.

    Note this is only intended for small strings, and depending on the similarity and length of the Strings: this can be very expensive. Because it is expensive: this object caches all requested diffs for cheap retrieval. So periodically you may want to replace your TextDiff object to avoid store large sets of Strings and diffs in memory.

    This class can best be described by examples, so let's consider how this diffs the two strings: "antigravity" and "gravity field". The simplest result this identifies is: "[anti]gravity{ field}". A visualization of this result resembles:

    You can either follow the red arrows (branch A, using square brackets) to create the first String, or you can follow the blue arrows (branch B, using curly brackets) to create the second String.

    Each of these columns is a different type of TextDiff.DiffSegment object:

    • TextDiff.SharedSegment: clusters of letters that belong to both of the Strings/branches. In the example above this is the middle column.
    • TextDiff.SplitSegment: clusters of letters that belong exclusively to branch A or B. In the example above this is the leftmost and rightmost column.

    One of the reasons that calculating these diffs is so expensive is that there may be several unusual ways to process this data. For example, this is another solution to the example above: "[an]{gravi}t[igrav]{y f}i[ty]{eld}":

    There are actually 38 solutions for this example. There are 74 solutions for diffing "agri department" against "agriculture dept". But in both cases: there is exactly one solution that is considered the simplest, so other solutions are discarded.

    Each solution is represented as a single DiffSegment object. A DiffSegment is actually a linked list, and you can traverse the next() and previous() methods to walk the list from beginning to end.

      • getSolutions

        public TextDiff.DiffSegment[] getSolutions(java.lang.String strA,
                                           java.lang.String strB)
        Return the simplest graphs explaining the diff between strA and strB.

        If this query is already cached, then that cached value is immediately returned. Otherwise this method calculates the diff and caches the results in this object for future retrieval.

        Parameters:
        strA - the first String/branch to compare.
        strB - the second String/branch to compare.
        Returns:
        the simplest graphs explaining the diff between strA and strB.

      • getSolutions

        public TextDiff.DiffSegment[] getSolutions(java.lang.String strA,
                                           java.lang.String strB,
                                           boolean includeAllSolutions)
        Return the graphs explaining the diff between strA and strB.

        If this query is already cached, then that cached value is immediately returned. Otherwise this method calculates the diff and caches the results in this object for future retrieval.

        Parameters:
        strA - the first String/branch to compare.
        strB - the second String/branch to compare.
        includeAllSolutions - if true then this includes ALL solutions, including overly complex solutions. If false (which is recommended) then this method only includes the simplest solutions. If all solutions are included: this query can be several times slower.
        Returns:
        the graphs explaining the diff between strA and strB.

      • processSolution

        protected void processSolution(java.util.Collection<TextDiff.DiffSegment> results,
                               TextDiff.DiffSegment solution,
                               com.pump.text.TextDiff.Key key,
                               com.pump.text.TextDiff.Complexity minComplexity)
        This chooses to record the results in the collection provided or discard it.

        If includeAllSolutions is true, then this solution is always recorded. Otherwise this solution is only recorded if the complexity is the lowest complexity yet detected.

        Parameters:
        results - the collection to store the solution in if this method decides to keep it.
        solution - the new solution to process.
        key - the key describing the query being made.

      • getSubset

        public TextDiff.DiffSegment getSubset(java.lang.String smallerPhrase,
                                      java.lang.String biggerPhrase)
        Return true if the smaller phrase is a subset of the bigger phrase. For example "cm" is a subset of "centimeter" and "camp".
        Parameters:
        smallerPhrase - the smaller of the two phrases (the one that might be an abbreviation)
        biggerPhrase - the larger of the two phrases
        Returns:
        the first solution that diffs these two phrases with the first as a subset as the second.
